I really loved it&hellip;
I was skeptical at first (I&rsquo;ve been burned too many times by boring and tropey fantasy novels that so many people love) but V. E. Schwab reeled me in with some gritty and edgy fantasy that felt really &ldquo;real&rdquo; to me.
I was so immersed in the world that I was tearing up by the end of the book which doesn&rsquo;t happen to me very often (one character&rsquo;s arc really spoke to me)

&ldquo;We&rsquo;re going on an adventure!&rdquo;
If you liked the previous novel in this series, Children of Time, you&rsquo;re likely to enjoy this one just as much if not more (I definitely did). If you haven&rsquo;t read it, I suggest you start with that one (also great) and then read this sequel. Otherwise, you&rsquo;ll be missing out.
Both novels take place in universes that feel very grounded in reality. The way in which the various species present evolve over time, communicate with each other, perceive the world around them and interact with it, feels satisfyingly plausible while simultaneously feeling truly alien.
